                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d467">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/327: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-10T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 10, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. Your 14, February 9, 3 p.m. Presumably the Greek authorities can expel Insull
                    without a passport since several countries admit American citizens who are not
                    in possession of such documents. However, if the Greek Government advises you
                    that it declines to expel him unless he is furnished with an American travel
                    document please inform the Department immediately by telegraph setting forth
                    full details as to destination and consideration will be given the matter. Is
                    the Greek Govt. concerned in expelling Insull or providing safe refuge for
                    him?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
